      "description": "A four-day harvest festival celebrated in Tamil Nadu with traditional rituals and feasts. Pongal is one of the most important and widely celebrated festivals in the state of Tamil Nadu, India. It is a multi-day harvest festival that marks the beginning of the sun’s northward journey (Uttarayana) and is dedicated to the Sun God (Surya). Pongal typically takes place in mid-January, usually from January 14th to January 17th, coinciding with Makar Sankranti, which is celebrated in different forms across India. The festival is named after the traditional dish 'Pongal,' which is made from the freshly harvested rice and symbolizes prosperity and abundance."
          "\n\nSignificance of Pongal:"
          "\n\nPongal is deeply rooted in agrarian culture and is primarily a celebration of the bountiful harvest that sustains life. It is a time for farmers to express gratitude to nature, the Sun God, the rain, and the cattle for their contributions to a successful harvest. Pongal signifies the end of the traditional farming season, giving farmers a break from their strenuous work and allowing them to enjoy the fruits of their labor."
          "\nThe Four Days of Pongal:"
          "\n\nPongal is celebrated over four days, each with its unique significance and rituals:"
          "\n\nBhogi Pongal (Day 1):"
          "\n\nBhogi Pongal marks the first day of the festival and is dedicated to Lord Indra, the god of rain, who is worshipped for providing rain for the harvest."
          "\n\nOn this day, people clean their homes thoroughly and discard old, unwanted items by lighting bonfires, symbolizing the destruction of old things to make way for new beginnings."
          "\n\nHouses are decorated with fresh kolam (rangoli) designs made from rice flour, and homes are adorned with mango leaves and flowers."
          "\nThai Pongal (Day 2):"
          "\n\nThai Pongal is the main day of the festival and is dedicated to the Sun God, Surya. This day usually coincides with Makar Sankranti, when the sun enters the zodiac sign of Capricorn (Makara)."
          "\n\nThe highlight of the day is the preparation of the Pongal dish, made by boiling freshly harvested rice with milk and jaggery in a new clay pot. As the rice boils over, people shout Pongalo Pongal! to celebrate the abundance and prosperity that the overflow symbolizes."
          "\n\nThe Pongal dish is offered to Surya as a mark of gratitude. This is followed by a feast with family members, where traditional vegetarian dishes are served on banana leaves."
          "\n\nPeople dress in new clothes, visit temples, and exchange gifts and sweets with friends and neighbors."
          "\n\nMattu Pongal (Day 3):"
          "\n\nMattu Pongal is dedicated to the worship of cattle, especially cows and bulls, which play a crucial role in agriculture by plowing fields and providing milk."
          "\n\nOn this day, cattle are bathed, their horns are painted, and they are adorned with garlands, bells, and colorful fabrics. Special prayers are offered, and the cattle are fed with the Pongal dish, fruits, and other delicacies."
          "\n\nMattu Pongal also includes various rural sports and traditional games, with the most famous being Jallikattu, a bull-taming sport that is particularly popular in the southern districts of Tamil Nadu."
          "\n\nIn some regions, the cattle are paraded through the streets, and villagers express their gratitude for their contributions to the harvest."
          "\n\nKaanum Pongal (Day 4):"
          "\n\nThe final day, Kaanum Pongal, is a day of relaxation and socialization. The word Kaanum means to visit, and it is customary for people to visit friends and family, exchange gifts, and enjoy the company of loved ones."
          "\n\nFamilies pack picnic lunches and visit nearby rivers, beaches, or parks, where they enjoy meals and engage in traditional games and activities."
          "\n\nIn some regions, women perform a special ritual known as Kanu Pidi, where they place leftover Pongal on turmeric leaves along with sugarcane, betel leaves, and nuts to feed birds and pray for the well-being of their brothers.",
